# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/1708-british-general-election] The **1708 British general election** was the first general election to be held after the Acts of Union had united the Parliaments of England and Scotland.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/1708-british-general-election] The election saw the Whigs gain a majority in the House of Commons, and by November the Whig-dominated parliament had succeeded in pressuring the Queen into accepting the Whig Junto into government for the first time since the late 1690s.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/1708-british-general-election] The Whigs only able to take partial control of the government, however, owing to the continued presence of the moderate Tory Godolphin in the cabinet (as Lord High Treasurer) and the opposition of the Queen.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/1708-british-general-election] Contests were held in 95 of the 269 English and Welsh constituencies and 28 of the 45 Scottish constituencies.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/1708-british-general-election] Following the election, Whig MP Lord Somers was appointed as Lord President of the Council.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/1708-british-general-election] However, moderate Tory Lord Godolphin remained as Lord High Treasurer and the Godolphin–Marlborough ministry remained in place.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/1708-british-general-election] In England, there were 513 MPs elected from 245 constituencies (203 boroughs, 40 counties, and 2 universities).
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/1708-british-general-election] In Wales, there were 24 MPs from 24 constituencies.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/1708-british-general-election] In Scotland, there were 45 MPs from 45 constituencies (30 counties and 15 burghs).
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/1708-british-general-election] The first general election held since the Union took place between 30 April 1708 and 7 July 1708.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/1708-british-general-election] At this period elections did not take place at the same time in every constituency.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/1708-british-general-election] The returning officer in each county or borough fixed the precise date (see hustings for details of the conduct of the elections).
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/1708-british-general-election] In England and Wales, the Whigs took 268 seats and the Tories took 225, with 20 unclassified.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/1708-british-general-election] The 45 in Scotland could be classified as ministerial supporters.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] The south-west of the county includes part of the Grampian Mountains.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] The historic county borders Kincardineshire, Angus and Perthshire to the south, Inverness-shire and Banffshire to the west, and the North Sea to the north and east.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] The area which would become Aberdeenshire was anciently occupied by the Picts, whom Ptolemy, writing c.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] There is some evidence of Roman activity in the area, notably with a camp at Normandykes near Peterculter.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Weems or earth-houses were a common type of ancient dwelling in the west.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Relics of crannogs or lake-dwellings exist at Loch Kinord and Bishops' Loch (historically called Loch Goul) in the parish of New Machar and elsewhere.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Duns or forts occur on hills at Dunecht, where the dun encloses an area of two acres (8,000 m2), Barra near Oldmeldrum, Tap o' Noth, Dunnideer near Insch and other places.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] There are numerous monoliths, standing stones and stone circles in the area, along with many examples of the sculptured stones of the early Christian epoch.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Missionaries aiming to convert the Picts to Christianity began with Teman in the 5th century, and continued with Columba, Machar (after whom St Machar's Cathedral in Aberdeen is named), and Drostan, who founded a monastery at Old Deer.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] The Vikings and Danes periodically raided the coast.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Macbeth, King of Scotland, was killed at the Battle of Lumphanan in 1057.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Aberdeen itself was made a royal burgh by David I (reigned 1124–1153).
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Its earliest surviving charter dates from 1179, by which date its burgesses had already combined with those of Banff, Elgin, Inverness and other trans-Grampian communities to form a hanse (trading league).
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] The Diocese of Aberdeen was in existence by the 1150s.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Like much of Scotland, the influence of clans led by powerful families was significant.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Many such clans in Aberdeenshire came to prominence in the 12th and 13th centuries, including the clans of Mar, Leslie, Bissett, Comyn and Cheyne.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] During the English invasion of 1296, the English army under Edward I took control of Aberdeen Castle.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] The following year, William Wallace surprised the English garrison in Aberdeen, but failed to capture the castle.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] In 1303 Edward again visited the county, halting at Kildrummy Castle, then in the possession of Robert the Bruce, who shortly afterwards became the acknowledged leader of the Scots and made Aberdeen his headquarters for several months.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] In 1308, he defeated John Comyn, Earl of Buchan, an opponent of his claim to the Scottish throne, at Inverurie.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] For a hundred years after Bruce's death in 1329, there was intermittent conflict in the shire.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] The English burned Aberdeen itself in 1336.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] The dispossession and re-settlement of the districts of Buchan and Strathbogie caused numerous disputes.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Moreover, the crown had embroiled itself with some of the Highland chieftains, whose independence it sought to abolish.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] This policy culminated in the invasion of Aberdeenshire by Donald of Islay, Lord of the Isles, who was defeated at the Battle of Harlaw in 1411 by the Scottish army under Alexander Stewart, Earl of Mar.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] In the 15th century two further leading county families emerged: Sir Alexander Forbes becoming Lord Forbes about 1442, and Sir Alexander Seton, Lord Gordon in 1437 and Earl of Huntly in 1445.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Bitter feuds raged between these families for a long period.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] The Gordons reached the height of their power in the first half of the 16th century, when their domains, already vast, were enhanced by the acquisition, through marriage, of the Earldom of Sutherland in 1514.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] King's College, Aberdeen was founded in 1495, followed by Marischal College in 1593; the two colleges subsequently merged to become the University of Aberdeen in 1860.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] In 1592, the shortlived Fraserburgh University was founded, thus for a short time, Aberdeenshire hosted three universities.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] The Reformation of the 16th century was slow to reach Aberdeenshire.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Churches were still being built and decorated in the old Catholic style in Aberdeenshire for some years after southern Scotland had started moving away from such styles.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Opposition to the changes to Protestant forms of worship and church leadership saw rioting in Aberdeen, with St Machar's Cathedral being damaged.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] George Gordon, 4th Earl of Huntly offered some resistance on behalf of the Catholics to the influence of James Stewart, 1st Earl of Moray, who was regent during the reign of James VI, but was defeated and killed at the Battle of Corrichie on the Hill of Fare in 1562.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] As years passed it became apparent that Presbyterianism gained less support in Aberdeenshire than Episcopacy, of which system Aberdeenshire remained for generations the stronghold in Scotland.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Another crisis in ecclesiastical affairs arose in 1638, when the authorities ordered subscription to the National Covenant.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] The people of Aberdeenshire responded so grudgingly to this demand that James Graham, 1st Marquess of Montrose, visited the shire in the following year to enforce acceptance.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] The Cavaliers, not being disposed to yield, dispersed an armed gathering of Covenanters in the affair called the Trot of Turriff in 1639, one of the first skirmishes in the Civil Wars.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] On 6 September 1715 John Erskine, Earl of Mar initiated the Jacobite rising of 1715 at Braemar in support of the claim of James Francis Edward Stuart to the throne.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Stuart arrived in Scotland from his exile in France, landing at Peterhead on 22 December 1715.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] The rising was unsuccessful and by February 1716 Stuart was back in France.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] The collapse of the 1715 rising ruined many of the lairds.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] In the subsequent Jacobite rising of 1745 there was much less support for the cause in the county, although the insurgents held Aberdeen for five months until February 1746.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] In 1852 Prince Albert, husband of Queen Victoria, bought the Balmoral Castle estate in the valley of the River Dee and subsequently rebuilt the castle there.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Aberdeenshire's origins as a shire (the area administered by a sheriff) are obscure.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] There is some evidence that it was a shire from the time of David I (reigned 1124–1153), but the earliest documented Sheriff of Aberdeen was in the 13th century.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] The sheriff's jurisdiction covered the older provinces of Buchan, Formartine, Garioch, and Marr (or Mar).
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Over time, Scotland's shires became more significant than the old provinces, with more administrative functions being given to the sheriffs.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] In 1667 Commissioners of Supply were established for each shire, which would serve as the main administrative body for the area until the creation of county councils in 1890.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Following the Acts of Union in 1707, the English term 'county' came to be used interchangeably with the older term 'shire'.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Elected county councils were established in 1890 under the Local Government (Scotland) Act 1889, taking most of the functions of the commissioners (which were eventually abolished in 1930).
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] The burgh of Aberdeen was deemed capable of providing its own county-level local government functions, and so it was excluded from the administrative area of the county council, although the county council still chose to base itself in the city.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] The first meeting of Aberdeenshire County Council was held on 22 May 1890 at Aberdeen Town House, which as well as being the headquarters of Aberdeen Corporation also served as the county's main courthouse and meeting place of the commissioners of supply.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Alexander Morison Gordon of Newton House in the parish of Culsalmond was the first convener of the council.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] The 1889 Act also led to a review of boundaries, with exclaves being transferred to a county they actually bordered, and parish and county boundaries being adjusted to eliminate cases where parishes straddled county boundaries.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] There were several such changes affecting the boundaries of Aberdeenshire.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] The city of Aberdeen, already independent for local government purposes, was subsequently also removed from Aberdeenshire for lieutenancy and other purposes in 1899, when the city was made a county of itself.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Shortly after its creation, the county council built itself County Buildings in Union Terrace, Aberdeen, to serve as its headquarters, which was completed in 1896.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] In 1975 the Local Government (Scotland) Act 1973 reorganised local government in Scotland into a two-tier system of regions and districts.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] The administrative counties of Aberdeenshire, the City of Aberdeen, Banffshire, Kincardineshire and most of Moray were merged to form Grampian Region, with the pre-1975 area of Aberdeenshire being divided between the districts of City of Aberdeen, Banff and Buchan, Gordon and Kincardine and Deeside.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] In 1996 the Scottish local government system was reorganised again, this time into single-tier council areas.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] One of the council areas is called Aberdeenshire, covering the combined area of the pre-1996 districts of Banff and Buchan, Gordon, and Kincardine and Deeside.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] The council area therefore has significantly different boundaries to the pre-1975 county, also including most of the historic county of Kincardineshire and eastern parts of Banffshire (including its county town of Banff), but excluding Aberdeen City.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] The boundaries of the historic county (as it was prior to the removal of Aberdeen in 1899) are still used for some limited official purposes connected with land registration, being a registration county.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] The Aberdeenshire lieutenancy area covers the area of the pre-1975 county excluding the parts within the modern Aberdeen City council area.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] The interior mountains of the Cairngorms provide the most striking of the physical features of the county.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] The chief rivers are the Dee, 90 miles (140 km) long; the Don, 82 miles (132 km); the Ythan, 37 miles (60 km), with mussel-beds at its mouth; the Ugie, 20 miles (32 km), and the Deveron, 62 miles (100 km), partly on the boundary of Banffshire.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] A pearl in the Scottish crown is said to be from the Ythan.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Loch Muick, the largest of the few lakes in the county, 399 m (1,309 ft) above the sea, 2+1⁄2 miles (4.0 km) long and 1⁄3 to 1⁄2 mile (540 to 800 m) broad, lies some 8+1⁄2 miles (13.7 km) southwest of Ballater.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Loch Strathbeg, 6 miles (9.7 km) southeast of Fraserburgh, is only separated from the sea by a narrow strip of land.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] There are noted chalybeate springs at Peterhead, Fraserburgh, and Pannanich near Ballater.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Other lochs of note are Loch Kinord, Loch Davan, Dubh Loch, Lochnagar, Loch Callater, Loch nan Eun and the Loch of Skene.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] The greater part of the county is composed of crystalline schists belonging to the metamorphic rocks of the Eastern Highlands.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] These divisions are folded on highly inclined or vertical axes trending north-east and south-west, and hence the same zones are repeated over a considerable area.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] The quartzite is generally regarded as the highest member of the series.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Excellent sections showing the component strata occur in Glen Clunie and its tributary valleys above Braemar.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Eastwards down the Dee and the Don and northwards across the plain of Buchan towards Rattray Head and Fraserburgh there is a development of biotite gneiss, partly of sedimentary and perhaps partly of igneous origin.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] A belt of slate which has been quarried for roofing purposes runs along the west border of the county from Turriff by Auchterless and the Foudland Hills towards the Tap o' Noth near Gartly.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] The metamorphic rocks have been invaded by igneous materials, some before, and by far the larger series after the folding of the strata.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] The basic types of the former are represented by the sills of epidiorite and hornblende gneiss in Glen Muick and Glen Callater, which have been permeated by granite and pegmatite in veins and lenticles, often foliated.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] The later granites subsequent to the plication of the schists have a wide distribution on the Ben Macdhui and Ben Avon range, and on Lochnagar; they stretch eastwards from Ballater by Tarland to Aberdeen and north to Bennachie.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Isolated masses appear at Peterhead and at Strichen.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Though consisting mainly of biotite granite, these later intrusions pass by intermediate stages into diorite, as in the area between Balmoral and the head-waters of the River Gairn.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] The granites have been extensively quarried at Rubislaw, Peterhead and Kemnay.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Serpentinite and troctolite, the precise age of which is uncertain, occur at the Black Dog Rock north of Aberdeen, at Belhelvie and near Oldmeldrum.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Where the schists of sedimentary origin have been pierced by these igneous intrusions, they are charged with contact minerals such as sillimanite, cordierite, kyanite and andalusite.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Cordierite-bearing rocks occur near Ellon, at the foot of Bennachie, and on the top of the Buck of Cabrach.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] A banded and mottled calc-silicate hornfels occurring with the limestone at Derry Falls, west-northwest of Braemar, has yielded malacolite, wollastonite, brown idocrase, garnet, sphene and hornblende.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] A larger list of minerals has been obtained from an exposure of limestone and associated beds in Glen Gairn, about four miles (6 km) above the point where that river joins the Dee.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Narrow belts of Old Red Sandstone, resting unconformably on the old platform of slates and schists, have been traced from the north coast at Peterhead by Turriff to Fyvie, and also from Huntly by Gartly to Kildrummy Castle.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] The strata consist mainly of conglomerates and sandstones, which, at Gartly and at Rhynie, are associated with lenticular bands of andesite indicating contemporaneous volcanic action.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Small outliers of conglomerate and sandstone of this age have recently been found in the course of excavations in Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] The glacial deposits, especially in the belt bordering the coast between Aberdeen and Peterhead, furnish important evidence.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] At a later date the local glaciers laid down materials on top of the red clay.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] The committee appointed by the British Association proved that the Greensand, which has yielded a large suite of Cretaceous fossils at Moreseat in the parish of Cruden, occurs in glacial drift, resting probably on granite.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] The strata from which the Moreseat fossils were derived are not now found in place in that part of Scotland.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Chalk flints are widely distributed in the drift between Fyvie and the east coast of Buchan.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] At Plaidy a patch of clay with Liassic fossils occurs.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] At several localities between Logie Coldstone and Dinnet a deposit of diatomite (Kieselguhr) occurs beneath the peat.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] The tops of the highest mountains have an Arctic flora.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] At the royal lodge on Loch Muick, 411 m (1,348 ft) above the sea, grow larches, vegetables, currants, laurels, roses, etc.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Some ash-trees, 1 to 1.5 m (4 or 5 ft) in girth, grow at 400 m (1,300 ft) above the sea.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Trees, especially Scotch fir and larch, grow well, and Braemar has plentiful natural timber, said to surpass any in the north of Europe.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Stumps of Scotch fir and oak found in peat sometimes far exceed any now growing in size.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Moles occur at 550 m (1,800 ft) above the sea, and squirrels at 450 m (1,480 ft).
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Grouse, partridges and hares abound, and rabbits are often numerous.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Red deer abound in Braemar, which in 1911 had the most extensive deer forest in Scotland.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Except in the mountainous districts, Aberdeenshire has a comparatively mild climate, owing to the proximity of much of the shire to the sea.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] The mean annual temperature at Braemar reaches 6 °C (43 °F), and that at Aberdeen 8 °C (46 °F).
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] The mean yearly rainfall varies from about 750 to 950 mm (30 to 37 in).
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] In summer the upper Dee and Don valleys provide the driest and most bracing climate in the British Isles, and grain grows cultivated up to 500 m (1,600 ft) above the sea, or 100 to 150 m (330 to 490 ft) higher than elsewhere in North Britain.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Poor, gravelly, clayey and peaty soils prevail, but tile-draining, bones and guano, and the best methods of modern tillage, greatly increased the produce.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Indeed, in 1911, no part of Scotland had a more productive soil developed out of such unpromising material.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Farm-houses and steadings have much improved, and the best agricultural implements and machines get widespread use.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] About two-thirds of the population depend entirely on agriculture.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Farms are small compared with those in the south-eastern counties.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Oats form the predominant crop, wheat has practically gone out of cultivation, but barley has largely increased.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] The most distinctive industry in 1911 was cattle-feeding.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Aberdeenshire fattens a great number of the home-bred crosses for the London and local markets, and imports Irish animals on an extensive scale for the same purpose, while an exceedingly heavy trade in dead meat for London and the south occurs all over the county.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Farmers also raise sheep, horses and pigs in large numbers.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Since the encyclopedia article was published in 1911, there have been significant changes.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Few Irish cattle now come in, the area is still famed for cattle, more commonly continental breeds, with most slaughtered in Scotland, and in particular a good local abattoir capacity.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Spring Barley is the predominant crop, and in lowland Winter Wheat, Oil Seed Rape & Potatoes would be more common than oats.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] There is also a significant area of carrots grown.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] With no slaughter capacity in Scotland the pig industry is diminishing but still a very important part of the North East economy.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Farm sizes are perhaps still relatively smaller than UK but there are some significant agribusinesses in Aberdeenshire.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Few farmers raise horses, though horses are more common, kept by private owners & specialists, than in any other area of Scotland.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] In 1911 a large fishing population in villages along the coast engage in the white and herring fishery, fostering the next most important industry to agriculture.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Aberdeenshire fishing developed almost exclusively due to the introduction of steam trawlers.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] In 1911 the total value of the annual catch, of which between a half and a third consists of herrings, amounts to £1,000,000.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] In 1911 the industry produced both speldings (salted and rock-dried haddocks) and finnans (smoked haddocks).
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] The ports and creeks belong to the fishery districts of Peterhead, Fraserburgh and Aberdeen, the last of which includes also three Kincardineshire ports.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] The herring season for Aberdeen, Peterhead and Fraserburgh lasts from June to September, at which time the ports become crowded with boats from other Scottish districts.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Valuable salmon-fishings exist – rod, net and stake-net – on the Dee, Don, Ythan and Ugie.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] In 1911 the average annual despatch of salmon from Aberdeenshire comprises about 400 long tons (450 short tons).
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] A number of paper-making establishments operate, most of them on the Don near Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] In 1911 the chief mineral wealth comes from the noted durable granite, quarried at Aberdeen, Kemnay, Peterhead and elsewhere including for causewaying stones.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Sandstone and other rocks are also quarried at different parts.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] The shire imports mostly coal, lime, timber, iron, slate, raw materials for the textile manufactures, wheat, cattle-feeding stuffs, bones, guano, sugar, alcoholic liquors, fruits.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] The exports include granite (rough-dressed and polished), flax, woollen and cotton goods, paper, combs, preserved provisions, oats, barley, and live and dead cattle.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] In last quarter of the 20th Century and into the 21st the North Sea oil industry was to become a large employer and overseas revenue earner.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Much of the industry's onshore facilities are based in Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] On the south, Aberdeen has rail links with Stonehaven, Montrose and Dundee, and to the north-west a line runs to Inverness via Huntly, Keith and Elgin.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Branch lines from various points used to run to several smaller towns, e.g. from Aberdeen to Ballater by Deeside, from Aberdeen to Fraserburgh (with a branch at Maud for Peterhead and at Ellon for Cruden Bay and Boddam), from Kintore to Alford, and from Inverurie to Oldmeldrum and also to Macduff.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] These lines all closed, largely as a result of the Beeching Axe in the 1960s, they now serve as local pathways or bicycle tracks.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] By sea Aberdeenshire has regular communication with the Orkney Islands and the Shetland Islands.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] The highest of the macadamized roads crossing the eastern Grampians rises to a point 2,200 ft (670 m) above sea-level.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Over the 20th Century road and air communications have improved.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Aberdeen Airport is an international airport, located at Dyce, a suburb of Aberdeen, approximately 5 nautical miles (9.3 km; 5.8 mi) north-west of Aberdeen city centre.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] A total of nearly 3.5 million passengers used the airport in 2015, a fall of 6.8% compared with 2014.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] In 1901 Aberdeenshire had 8 persons who spoke Gaelic only, and 1333 who spoke Gaelic and English.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] In 1911 the Supreme Court of Justiciary sat in Aberdeen to try cases from the counties of Aberdeen, Banff and Kincardine.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] The three counties are under a sheriff, and two sheriffs-substitute reside in Aberdeen, and also sat at Fraserburgh, Huntly, Peterhead and Turriff.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] The sheriff courts occurred in Aberdeen and Peterhead.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] The higher branches of education have always been thoroughly taught in the schools throughout the shire, and pupils have long been in the habit of going directly from the schools to the university.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] According to the 1911 Encyclopædia, Aberdeenshire people have a quick, sharp, rather angry accent.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] The local Scots dialect, affectionately known as the Doric, appears broad, and rich in diminutives, and is noted for the use of /i/ in *bane* and *stane* and *muin* but /wi/ before /g/ and /k/ in *guid* and *cuit* etc., the /f/ realisation of *wh*, /d/ for medial *th* /ð/ etc.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] As recently as 1830 Gaelic provided the fireside language of almost every family in Braemar, but by the start of the 20th century was little used.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] The coat of arms of **Aberdeenshire County Council** was granted in 1890.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] The four quarters represented the Buchan, Mar, Garioch and Strathbogie areas.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] In 2023, a competition was held to choose a county flag.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] The result, a flag designed by local school pupils, was raised at Castle Fraser on 22 April 2023.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] There was an Aberdeenshire constituency of the House of Commons of the Parliament of Great Britain from 1708 to 1801 and of the Parliament of the United Kingdom from 1801 to 1868.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] This constituency did not include the parliamentary burgh of Aberdeen, which was represented as a component of Aberdeen District of Burghs until 1832, when it was enlarged and became the Aberdeen burgh constituency.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] The other components of the district of burghs became components of the then new Montrose District of Burghs.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] In 1868 the Aberdeenshire constituency was divided to form two new county divisions, or *county constituencies*, namely Eastern Aberdeenshire and Western Aberdeenshire.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] In 1885 the Aberdeen burgh constituency was divided to form the burgh constituencies of Aberdeen North and Aberdeen South.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Kincardine and Western Aberdeenshire included the whole of the former Kincardineshire constituency.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] Boundary changes in 1955 enlarged the Aberdeenshire West constituency, and reduced the size of the Aberdeenshire East constituency.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-historic] In 1983, eight years after the local government county of Aberdeenshire was abolished, the Aberdeenshire constituencies were replaced with new constituencies.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency] Before the Acts of Union 1707, the barons of the **shire of Aberdeen** elected commissioners to represent them in the unicameral Parliament of Scotland and in the Convention of the Estates.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency] The number of commissioners was increased from two to four in 1690.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency] From 1708 Aberdeenshire was represented by one Member of Parliament in the House of Commons of Great Britain.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-uk-parliament-constituency] In 1868 it was divided to create Eastern Aberdeenshire and Western Aberdeenshire.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-uk-parliament-constituency] The British parliamentary constituency was created in 1708 following the Acts of Union 1707 and replaced the former Parliament of Scotland shire constituency of Aberdeenshire .
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-uk-parliament-constituency] When created in 1708, the constituency covered the county of Aberdeen minus the burgh of Aberdeen, which was part of the Aberdeen Burghs constituency.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-uk-parliament-constituency] Under the Representation of the People (Scotland) Act 1832 the Aberdeen burgh constituency was created to cover the burgh plus areas previously within the Aberdeenshire constituency.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-uk-parliament-constituency] The constituency elected one Member of Parliament (MP) by the first past the post system until the seat was abolished for the 1868 general election.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-uk-parliament-constituency] In 1868, the Representation of the People (Scotland) Act 1868 divided Aberdeenshire to form Eastern Aberdeenshire and Western Aberdeenshire, and these new constituencies were first used in the 1868 general election.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-uk-parliament-constituency] Gordon was appointed a Lord Commissioner of the Admiralty, requiring a by-election.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-uk-parliament-constituency] Gordon resigned by accepting the office of Steward of the Chiltern Hundreds, causing a by-election.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-uk-parliament-constituency] Hamilton-Gordon succeeded as 5th Earl of Aberdeen, and had thus become ineligible to sit in the House of Commons.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/aberdeenshire-uk-parliament-constituency] The ensuing by-election was won by the Conservative candidate, William Leslie.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] The **Acts of Union** refer to two acts of Parliament, one by the Parliament of Scotland in March 1707, followed shortly thereafter by an equivalent act of the Parliament of England.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] They put into effect the international Treaty of Union agreed on 22 July 1706, which politically joined the Kingdom of England and Kingdom of Scotland into a single "political state" named Great Britain, with Queen Anne as its sovereign.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] The English and Scottish acts of ratification took effect on 1 May 1707, creating the new kingdom, with its parliament based in the Palace of Westminster.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] The two countries had shared a monarch since the "personal" Union of the Crowns in 1603, when James VI of Scotland inherited the English throne from his cousin Elizabeth I to become (in addition) 'James I of England', styled James VI and I.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] Prior to 1603, England and Scotland had different monarchs, but when Elizabeth I died without children, she was succeeded as King of England by her distant relative, James VI of Scotland.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] After her death, the two Crowns were held in personal union by James (reigning as James VI and I), who announced his intention to unite the two realms.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] The 1603 Union of England and Scotland Act established a joint Commission to agree terms, but the Parliament of England was concerned this would lead to an absolutist structure similar to that of Scotland.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] James was forced to withdraw his proposals, but used the royal prerogative to take the title "King of Great Britain".
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] Attempts to revive the project of union in 1610 were met with hostility.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] English opponents such as Sir Edwin Sandys argued that changing the name of England "were as yf [*sic*] to make a conquest of our name, which was more than ever the Dane or Norman could do".
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] Instead, James set about creating a unified Church of Scotland and England, as the first step towards a centralised, Unionist state.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] However, despite both being nominally Episcopal in structure, the two were very different in doctrine; the Church of Scotland, or kirk, was Calvinist in doctrine, and viewed many Church of England practices as little better than Catholicism.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] As a result, attempts to impose religious policy by James and his son Charles I ultimately led to the 1639–1651 Wars of the Three Kingdoms.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] The 1639–1640 Bishops' Wars confirmed the primacy of the Scots kirk, and established a Covenanter government in Scotland.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] The Scots remained neutral when the First English Civil War began in 1642, before becoming concerned at the impact on Scotland of an English Royalist victory.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] Presbyterian leaders like Argyll viewed union as a way to ensure free trade between England and Scotland, and preserve a Scots Presbyterian kirk.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] Under the 1643 Solemn League and Covenant, the Scots Parliament agreed to provide military support to its English counterpart in return for a united Presbyterian church, but did not explicitly commit to political union.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] As the war progressed, Scots and English Presbyterians increasingly viewed the English Independents, and associated radical groups like the Levellers, as a bigger threat than the Royalists.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] Both Royalists and Presbyterians agreed monarchy was divinely ordered, but disagreed on the nature and extent of Royal authority over the church.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] When Charles I surrendered in 1646, an English pro-Royalist faction known as the Engagers allied with their former enemies to restore him to the English throne.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] After defeat in the 1647–1648 Second English Civil War, Scotland was occupied by English troops, which were withdrawn once those whom Cromwell held responsible had been replaced by the Kirk Party.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] In December 1648, Pride's Purge paved the way for the Trial of Charles I in England by excluding MPs who opposed it.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] Following the execution of Charles I in January 1649, and establishment of the Commonwealth of England, the Scots Kirk Party proclaimed Charles II King of Scots and England and, in the 1650 Treaty of Breda, resolved to restore him to the English throne.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] Instead, defeat in the Anglo-Scottish War resulted in Scotland's incorporation into the Commonwealth in 1653, largely driven by Cromwell's determination to break the power of the Scots kirk.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] The 1652 Tender of Union was followed on 12 April 1654 by *An Ordinance by the Protector for the Union of England and Scotland,* creating the Commonwealth of England and Scotland.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] It was ratified by the Second Protectorate Parliament on 26 June 1657, creating a single Parliament in Westminster, with 30 representatives each from Scotland and Ireland added to the existing English members.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] While integration into the Commonwealth established free trade between Scotland and England, the economic benefits were diminished by the costs of military occupation.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] Both Scotland and England associated union with heavy taxes and military rule; it had little popular support in either Country, and the union was dissolved after the Restoration of Charles II in 1660.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish economy was badly damaged by the (protectionist) English Navigation Acts of 1660 and 1663 and England's wars with the Dutch Republic, Scotland's major export market.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] An Anglo-Scots Trade Commission was set up in January 1668 but the English had no interest in making concessions, as the Scots had little to offer in return.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] In 1669, Charles II revived talks on "political union"; his motives may have been to weaken Scotland's commercial and political links with the Dutch, still seen as an enemy and complete the work of his grandfather James I and VI.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] On the Scottish side, the proposed union received parliamentary support, boosted by the desire to ensure free trade.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] Continued opposition meant these negotiations were abandoned by the end of 1669.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] The Convention of the Estates issued an address to William and Mary "as both kingdomes are united in one head and soveraigne so they may become one body pollitick, one nation to be represented in one parliament", reserving "our church government, as it shall be established at the tyme of the union".
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] William and Mary were supportive of the idea but it was opposed both by the Presbyterian majority in Scotland and the English Parliament.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] Episcopacy in Scotland was abolished in 1690, alienating a significant part of the political class; it was this element that later formed the bedrock of opposition to Union.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] The 1690s were a time of economic hardship in Europe as a whole and Scotland in particular, a period now known as the Seven ill years which led to strained relations with England.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] In 1698, the Company of Scotland Trading to Africa and the Indies received a charter to raise capital through public subscription.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] The Company invested in the Darién scheme, an ambitious plan funded almost entirely by Scottish investors to build a colony on the Isthmus of Panama for trade with East Asia.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] The scheme was a disaster; the losses of over £150,000 severely impacted the Scottish commercial system.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] The International Treaty, and English and Scots acts of ratification of Union may be seen within a wider European context of increasing state centralisation during the late 17th and early 18th centuries, including the monarchies of France, Sweden, Denmark-Norway and Spain.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] While there were exceptions, such as the Dutch Republic or the Republic of Venice, the trend was clear.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] The dangers of the monarch using one parliament against the other first became apparent in 1647 and 1651.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] It resurfaced during the 1679 to 1681 Exclusion Crisis, caused by English resistance to the Catholic prince James (later James II of England, James VII of Scots) succeeding his brother Charles II.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] It then went beyond ensuring James's succession to the Scots throne by explicitly stating the aim was to make his exclusion from the English throne impossible without "the fatall and dreadfull consequences of a civil war".
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] The issue reappeared during the 1688 Dutch invasion and *coup d'etat* (subsequently entitled as "the Glorious Revolution").
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] The English Convention Parliament generally supported replacing James with his Protestant daughter Mary, holding to their "legal fiction" that James, by fleeing to France, had abandoned his English subjects and "abdicated".
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] They initially resisted making her Dutch husband William of Orange joint ruler but relented, "fearing the return of James" only when William threatened to take his troops and fleet and return to the Netherlands, and Mary refused to rule without him.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, it became a Constitutional issue.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] The fact that King James had not been present in Scotland meant that the question of abdication need not arise.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] On 4 April 1689 a Convention of the Three Estates of Scotland (sister body to the Parliament of Scotland) declared that James "had acted irregularly" by assuming regal power (government) "without ever taking the Coronation Oath required by Scots Law".
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] Thus, he had "FOREFALTED [forfeited] the Right to the Scots Crown, and the Scots Throne is become vacant".
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] "Scots monarchs derived legitimacy from the Convention of the Estates", later declared a Parliament of Scotland, not God, thus ending the principle of divine right of kings.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] Conflict over control of the kirk between Presbyterians and Episcopalians and William's position as a fellow Calvinist put him in a much stronger position.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] He originally insisted on retaining Episcopacy, and the Committee of the Articles, an unelected body that controlled what legislation Parliament could debate.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] Both would have given the Crown far greater control than in England but he withdrew his demands due to the 1689–1692 Jacobite Rising.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] 2. the Convention of the Estates was a parliament and so parliament could just rewrite it.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] Here is the Claim of Right understood and upheld for its secular constitutional provisions quite as much as for its religious provisions.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] The English succession was provided for by the English Act of Settlement 1701, which ensured that the monarch of England would be a Protestant member of the House of Hanover.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] Until the union of parliaments, the Scottish throne might be inherited by a different successor after Queen Anne, who had said in her first speech to the English parliament that a union was "very necessary".
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish Act of Security 1704, however, was passed after the English parliament, without consultation with Scotland, had designated Electoress Sophia of Hanover (granddaughter of James I and VI) as Anne's successor, if Anne died childless.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] The Act of Security granted the Parliament of Scotland, the three Estates, the right to choose a successor and explicitly required a choice different from the English monarch unless the English were to grant free trade and navigation.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] Then the Alien Act 1705 was passed in the English parliament, designating Scots in England as "foreign nationals" and blocking about half of all Scottish trade by boycotting exports to England or its colonies, unless Scotland came back to negotiate a Union.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] To encourage a union, "honours, appointments, pensions and even arrears of pay and other expenses were distributed to clinch support from Scottish peers and MPs".
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish economy was severely impacted by privateers during the 1688–1697 Nine Years' War and the 1701 War of the Spanish Succession, with the Royal Navy focusing on protecting English ships.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] This compounded the economic pressure caused by the Darien scheme, and the seven ill years of the 1690s, when 5–15% of the population died of starvation.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish Parliament was promised financial assistance, protection for its maritime trade, and an end to economic restrictions on trade with England.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] The votes of the Court party, influenced by Queen Anne's favourite, James Douglas, 2nd Duke of Queensberry, combined with the majority of the Squadrone Volante, were sufficient to ensure passage of the treaty.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] The role played by bribery has long been debated. £20,000 was distributed by David Boyle, 1st Earl of Glasgow, of which 60% went to the Duke of Queensberry, the Queen's Commissioner in Parliament.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] Another negotiator, John Campbell, 2nd Duke of Argyll was given an English dukedom.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] Professor Sir Tom Devine agreed that promises of "favours, sinecures, pensions, offices and straightforward cash bribes became indispensable to secure government majorities".
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] As for representation going forwards, Scotland was, in the new united parliament, only to get 45 MPs, one more than Cornwall, and only 16 (unelected) peers in the House of Lords.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] There were mixed opinions in Scotland about the prospect of a union with England.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] Sir George Lockhart of Carnwath, the only Scottish negotiator to oppose Union, noted "the whole nation appears against (it)".
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] Another negotiator, Sir John Clerk of Penicuik, who was an ardent Unionist, observed it was "contrary to the inclinations of at least three-fourths of the Kingdom".
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] As the seat of the Scottish Parliament, demonstrators in Edinburgh feared the impact of its loss on the local economy.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] Elsewhere, there was widespread concern about the independence of the kirk, and possible tax rises.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] Virtually all of the print discourses of 1699–1706 spoke against incorporating union, creating the conditions for widespread rejection of the treaty in 1706 and 1707.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] In the wake of unionist proselytising in the autumn of 1706 and early 1707, many Scots were undecided about the prospect of a union.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] Rather, there was considerably more support in Scotland for a federal union with England than an incorporative one, similar to the devolved Scottish parliament that would be established within Britain nearly three centuries later.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] As the treaty passed through the Parliament of Scotland, opposition was voiced by petitions from shires, burghs, presbyteries and parishes.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] According to Christopher Whatley, however, calls for a union with England began in Scotland itself in the 1690s for the purpose of safeguarding the law, line of succession, and to improve the economy.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] Ireland, though a kingdom under the same crown, was not included in the union.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] It remained a separate kingdom, unrepresented in Parliament, and was legally subordinate to Great Britain until the Renunciation Act 1783.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] In July 1707 each House of the Parliament of Ireland passed a congratulatory address to Queen Anne, praying that "May God put it in your royal heart to add greater strength and lustre to your crown, by a still more comprehensive Union".
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] The British government did not respond to the invitation and an equal union between Great Britain and Ireland was out of consideration until the 1790s.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] The union with Ireland finally came about on 1 January 1801.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] Deeper political integration had been a key policy of Queen Anne from the time she acceded to the throne in 1702.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] Under the aegis of the Queen and her ministers in both kingdoms, the parliaments of England and Scotland (the **Act for a Treaty with England 1705**) agreed to participate in fresh negotiations for a union treaty in 1705.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] Both countries appointed 31 commissioners to conduct the negotiations.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] Most of the Scottish commissioners favoured union, and about half were government ministers and other officials.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] At the head of the list was the Duke of Queensberry, and the Lord Chancellor of Scotland, the Earl of Seafield.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] The English commissioners included the Lord High Treasurer, Sidney Godolphin, 1st Earl of Godolphin, the Lord Keeper of the Great Seal, William Cowper, Baron Cowper, and a large number of Whigs who supported union.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] Tories were not in favour of union and only one was represented among the commissioners.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] Negotiations between the English and Scottish commissioners took place between 16 April and 22 July 1706 at the Cockpit in London.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] Each side had its own particular concerns.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] After negotiations ended in July 1706, the acts had to be ratified by both Parliaments.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, about 100 of the 227 members of the Parliament of Scotland were supportive of the Court Party.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] For extra votes the pro-court side could rely on about 25 members of the Squadrone Volante, led by the James Graham, 4th Marquess of Montrose and John Ker, 1st Duke of Roxburghe.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] The Court party enjoyed significant funding from England and the Treasury and included many who had accumulated debts following the Darien Disaster.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] The act ratifying the Treaty of Union was finally carried in the Parliament of Scotland by 110 votes to 69 on 16 January 1707, with a number of key amendments.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] News of the ratification and of the amendments was received in Westminster, where the Act was passed quickly through both Houses and received the royal assent on 6 March.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] Though the English Act was later in date, it bore the year '1706' while Scotland's was '1707', as the legal year in England began only on 25 March.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, the Duke of Queensberry was largely responsible for the successful passage of the Union act by the Parliament of Scotland.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, he was greeted by stones and eggs but in England he was cheered for his action.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] He had personally received around half of the funding awarded by the Westminster Treasury.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] In April 1707, he travelled to London to attend celebrations at the royal court, and was greeted by groups of noblemen and gentry lined along the road.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] From Barnet, the route was lined with crowds of cheering people, and once he reached London a huge crowd had formed.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] On 17 April, the Duke was gratefully received by the Queen at Kensington Palace and the Acts came into effect on 1 May 1707.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] A day of thanksgiving was declared in England and Ireland but not in Scotland, where the bells of St Giles rang out the tune of *"why should I be so sad on my wedding day"*.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] The Treaty of Union, agreed between representatives of the Parliament of England and the Parliament of Scotland in 1706, consisted of 25 articles, 15 of which were economic in nature.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, each article was voted on separately and several clauses in articles were delegated to specialised subcommittees.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] Article 1 of the treaty was based on the political principle of an incorporating union and this was secured by a majority of 116 votes to 83 on 4 November 1706.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] To minimise the opposition of the Church of Scotland, an Act was also passed to secure the Presbyterian establishment of the Church, after which the Church stopped its open opposition, although hostility remained at lower levels of the clergy.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] The treaty as a whole was finally ratified on 16 January 1707 by a majority of 110 votes to 69.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] The two Acts incorporated provisions for Scotland to send representative peers from the Peerage of Scotland to sit in the House of Lords.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] It guaranteed that the Church of Scotland would remain the established church in Scotland, that the Court of Session would "remain in all time coming within Scotland", and that Scots law would "remain in the same force as before".
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] Other provisions included the restatement of the Act of Settlement 1701 and the ban on Roman Catholics from taking the throne.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] It also created a customs union and monetary union.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] The Act provided that any "laws and statutes" that were "contrary to or inconsistent with the terms" of the Act would "cease and become void".
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish Parliament also passed the Protestant Religion and Presbyterian Church Act 1707 guaranteeing the status of the Presbyterian Church of Scotland.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] The English Parliament passed a similar Act, 6 Ann. c.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] 40—later named the Union with Scotland (Amendment) Act 1707—united the Privy Council of England and Privy Council of Scotland and decentralised Scottish administration by appointing justices of the peace in each shire to carry out administration.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] In effect it took the day-to-day government of Scotland out of the hands of politicians and into those of the College of Justice.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] On 18 December 1707 the Act for better Securing the Duties of East India Goods was passed which extended the monopoly of the East India Company to Scotland.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] In the year following the Union, the Treason Act 1708 abolished the Scottish law of treason and extended the corresponding English law across Great Britain.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] Clark, gaining "freedom of trade with England and the colonies" as well as "a great expansion of markets".
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] The agreement guaranteed the permanent status of the Presbyterian church in Scotland, and the separate system of laws and courts in Scotland.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] However, the Scottish economy was lagging behind not only from the impact of wars, but also because of chronic deflation and industrial underdevelopment.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] Scotland remained a predominantly agrarian society, and the lack of manpower caused by previous conflicts contributed to an underwhelming agricultural output, which intermittently escalated into local food shortages or famines.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] In turn, the overreliance of Scottish landowners on foreign goods led to a deficit of financial capital, as gold and silver were exported overseas and deflation occurred.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish Parliament attempted to combat the issue by attracting foreign investment; duty on ship building materials was lifted, taxes on new manufacturing stocks were cut, and customs on textile and linen goods were removed.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] Scotland grew increasingly dependent on its linen industry, which became the biggest source of employment after agriculture and constituted one-third of Scottish industry.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] Continental linen industries could outcompete Scotland, and protectionist tariffs implemented by Scotland led to tariff wars as European countries closed their markets to Scotland.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] In this situation, England became the largest foreign market for Scottish linen; however, while the tariffs in place shielded Scotland from the much larger English industry, England also retaliated against them.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] This forced Scotland to seek economic alternatives.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] At the time, trade with colonies was rapidly growing in importance in Europe, and trade with colonies was very attractive to Scotland, given its pastoral economy.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] American colonies had a high demand of agricultural goods such as leather skins of goats and sheep, which would have provided Scotland a valuable source of income.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] Search for colonial trade, along with the frustration caused by economic and political rivalry with England, led to the Darien scheme – an unsuccessful attempt to establish a Scottish colony in the Gulf of Darién.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] The failure of the Darien scheme led to a financial crisis in Scotland.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] The high cost of its project exacerbated the deflation in Scotland.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] The Bank of Scotland had dangerously low reserves, and in early 1700s a run on the bank occurred, along with temporary suspension of business.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] Ultimately, the Scottish bank managed to stay solvent, although the persisting deflation and low reserves largely contributed to the feeling of Scottish economy being in a precarious position.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] Economist Aida Ramos argues that the Darien scheme could have succeeded if it was to receive support from either England or Spain, and that it lacked the capability to create a threat to England or its interests.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] According to Ramos, the English intervention against the scheme was to meet the expansionary aims of England, as to ensure both its colonial dominance as well as the annexation of Scotland.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] By 1703, the Scottish government was highly disillusioned with the union, and many believed that the only way to let the Scottish economy flourish was to separate from England.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] Scotland would try to establish further autonomy from England with the Act of Security 1704, which provoked a retaliation from England – Scottish ministers were bribed, and Alien Act 1705 was passed.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] According to the Alien Act, unless Scotland appointed commissioners to negotiate for union by Christmas, every Scot in England would be treated as an alien, leading to the confiscation of their English estates.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] Additionally, Scottish wares were to be banned from England.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish economy was now facing a crisis, and the parliament was polarised into pro-union and anti-union factions, with the former led by Daniel Defoe.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] The unionists stressed how important trade with England is to the Scottish economy, and seen trade with continental Europe as not beneficial.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] They argued that the Scottish economy could survive by trading with England, and sanctions that would result from the Alien Act would collapse the economy.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] For Defoe, joining the union would not only prevent the Alien Act, but also remove additional limitations and regulations and lead Scotland to prosperity.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] Anti-unionists questioned the English goodwill and criticised the unionist faction for submitting to the English blackmail.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] They argued that Scotland could make a recovery by trading with the Netherlands, Spain and Norway, allowing Scotland to diversify its own industries as well.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] They argued that the union would make Scotland unable to conduct independent trade policy, meaning that any possibility to remove the flaws in Scottish economy would be gone forever, which would turn Scotland into a "mere satellite of the richer kingdom".
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] Ultimately, Scottish ministers voted in favour of the union, despite the lack of public support, with the overwhelming majority of the Scottish population at the time protesting vociferously against any union with England.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] Many Scots considered themselves to have been betrayed by their own elites, and that the union bill was able to pass only thanks to English bribery.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] In the first few decades after the union, England did not end up becoming the main trading partner of Scotland, as other European powers became the primary source of imported goods for Scotland.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] For at least the first 40 years after the union, Scotland persisted in its traditional trade patterns, and the economic situation of Scotland was not as dire as that described in the months leading up to the Acts of Union.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] Christopher Whatley writes, however, that by 1799, it was reported that the union of Scotland with England had not only benefitted the Scottish economy, but promoted a "commercial prosperity" unknown to any people.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/acts-of-union-1707] A commemorative two-pound coin was issued to mark the tercentennial—300th anniversary—of the Union, which occurred two days before the Scottish Parliament general election on 3 May 2007.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/alexander-fraser-11th-lord-saltoun] Fraser was born in 1604 in the young town of Fraserburgh in Aberdeenshire, Scotland.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/alexander-fraser-11th-lord-saltoun] His father was Sir Alexander Fraser (1570–1636), and his mother was Lady Margaret Abernethy, daughter of Sir George Abernethy, 7th Lord Saltoun of Abernethy.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/alexander-fraser-11th-lord-saltoun] He entered King's College, Aberdeen, in 1619.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/alexander-fraser-11th-lord-saltoun] Upon the death of his father in 1636, he inherited the lands of Philorth as its 10th Laird.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/alexander-fraser-11th-lord-saltoun] Alexander subscribed the Solemn League and Covenant at Aberdeen in 1638 and was a member of the General Assembly of the Church of Scotland at Glasgow in 1639.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/alexander-fraser-11th-lord-saltoun] Also in 1639, while serving under the Earl of Montrose, he led 200 men against the castles of Kellie and Gight.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/alexander-fraser-11th-lord-saltoun] He was chosen as a commissioner for Aberdeenshire in 1643 and this capacity attended the Convention of Estates in Edinburgh.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/alexander-fraser-11th-lord-saltoun] After King Charles I was apprehended and taken to England, Saltoun took part in the failed rescue mission to England in 1648, commanding a regiment of Scots.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/alexander-fraser-11th-lord-saltoun] In the reign of Charles II, he is known to have lent large sums of money to the king.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/alexander-fraser-11th-lord-saltoun] He was a Member of Parliament for Aberdeenshire twice, first in 1648 and again in 1661-63.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/alexander-fraser-11th-lord-saltoun] During the English Civil War, he fought in the Royalist cause at the Battle of Worcester (1651) in which he was severely wounded and might have been killed had it not been for his servant, James Cardno, who rescued him, saw to his recovery and returned him to his home at Fraserburgh.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/alexander-fraser-11th-lord-saltoun] In 1669, Fraser served as commissioner for the visitation of the two colleges of Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/alexander-fraser-11th-lord-saltoun] In 1670, his succession to the Lordship of Saltoun of Abernethy was ratified by King Charles II and confirmed by Act of Parliament.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/alexander-fraser-11th-lord-saltoun] Alexander Fraser, now designated the 11th Lord Saltoun, was traditionally designated the 10th because after the death of the 9th Lord Saltoun (Alexander Abernethy, 1611-1668), his sister Margaret Fraser, née Abernethy (1616-1669), succeeded with the title 10th Lady Saltoun.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/alexander-fraser-11th-lord-saltoun] However, she survived her brother by only two and a half months, and the title passed to Alexander Fraser, cousin of the Abernethys through his maternal line.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/alexander-fraser-11th-lord-saltoun] In recent times, it was realized that Margaret had her title by the old Scots system of succession, and the decision was made to renumber the Lords Saltoun.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/alexander-fraser-11th-lord-saltoun] As a result, Lady Saltoun is designated the 10th in the succession with Alexander Fraser, accordingly, moving from 10th to 11th in the succession.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/alexander-fraser-11th-lord-saltoun] His first wife was Isobel Forbes of Tolquhorn, who bore him one daughter, Janet.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/alexander-fraser-11th-lord-saltoun] His second wife was Elizabeth Urquhart, née Seton, widow of John Urquhart of Craigfintrie and daughter of Alexander Seton of Meldrum.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/alexander-fraser-11th-lord-saltoun] She was the mother of Fraser's son, Alexander, who predeceased him in 1672, necessitating that the title of 12th Lord Saltoun pass to William Fraser (1654-1715), grandson of the 11th Lord.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/alexander-fraser-11th-lord-saltoun] Alexander Fraser, the 11th Lord Saltoun of Abernethy, died on 11 August 1693 at the age of 89.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/argyllshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency] Before the Acts of Union 1707, the barons of the **shire or sheriffdom of Argyll** elected commissioners to represent them in the unicameral Parliament of Scotland and in the Convention of the Estates.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/argyllshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency] The number of commissioners was increased from two to three in 1693.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/argyllshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency] From 1708 Argyllshire was represented by one Member of Parliament in the House of Commons of Great Britain.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/ayrshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency] Before the Acts of Union 1707, the Barons of the **Sheriffdom or Shire of Ayr** elected commissioners to represent them in the Parliament of Scotland and in the Convention of the Estates.
[src:aberdeenshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency/ayrshire-parliament-of-scotland-constituency] After the Union, Ayrshire returned one Member of Parliament to the House of Commons of Great Britain and later to the House of Commons of the United Kingdom.
